<p>Someone at the Sun or the Globeâ€™s digital business units could go through their dogâ€™s breakfast of a UX and explain why each individual item is there. A good case can be made for each, no doubt â€“ business interests, user surveys, clickthrough rates, etc.</p>

<p>But itâ€™s like watching a <a href="https://twitter.com/asymco/status/400297561124532224">Dr. Zasio</a> on <em>Hoarders</em> argue with a patient about why they donâ€™t need 40 vacuum cleaners. Yes, they are all in working condition and sweeping floors <em>is</em> important, but canâ€™t you take a step back, look at the big picture and see that this is bad?</p>

<p>But itâ€™s not one person responsible for the mess. It takes collective effort of an entire organization to achieve this. As they <a href="http://www.despair.com/meetings.html">say</a>, none of us is as dumb as all of us.</p>

<p>Here are a couple screenshots of the Denver Post that Iâ€™ve annotated in yellow using non-technical language to explain the UX problems and perhaps add some clarity to why bad UX is a problem.</p>
